@Scott

Right, thanks.

I still find the realization how many homophones there actually are in English quite amazing: there are very few of them in Polish, mostly because generally there is only one way of pronouncing a certain combination of letters in our language.

@Strudel Dad

I was puzzled because your wording could be understood as implying all those words are one syllable, and I've been surprised by English grammar and pronunciation so many times before that I'm always prepared to be amazed yet again.

Homophony is almost non-existent in Polish, for example, since our spelling pretty much always dictates only one way of pronouncing a word. The exceptions are few and far between, e.g. bóg (god), buk (beech tree), and the river Bug (a proper name with unclear etyomology) sound the same ("ó" and "u" are both the same sound in Polish, your "oo", and "g" and "k" sound essentialy the same at the end of a word).

@SBK in TO

How does that apply here? "IRATE" comes from the Latin "ira", anger. It's also not how "irritate" came to be: <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/irritate" target="_blank">https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/irritate</a>

The Latin "irritatus" spawned the English "irritated", as well as the Polish "poirytowany" ("po" is a suffix to the noun "irytacja" here, together forming an adjective) - we lost the second "r", as Polish generally does not use double-Rs, at all.

